# TESTING STANDARDS

> This file defines how tests are written, organized, and run in the City Asset Registry System.
> These standards apply to all contributors — human developers and AI agents alike.
> Tests are not optional. They are part of the feature.

---

## Why Testing Matters Here

This system manages government property records. A bug in the asset verification flow, the RBAC permission checks, or the reconciliation engine is not just a software problem — it is a governance failure. Tests are the primary mechanism for proving that the system behaves correctly, and they must be treated with the same seriousness as the production code they protect.

Beyond correctness, tests serve as **living documentation**. A well-written test suite tells the next developer (or AI agent) exactly what the system is supposed to do, without them having to read through layers of implementation code.

---

## Test Runner

All tests use **`vp test`** — Vitest, configured in `vite.config.ts`.

```bash
vp test                   # Run all tests once (CI mode)
vp test watch             # Watch mode during active development
vp test run --coverage    # Run with coverage report
```

**Do not use `bun test`.** Vitest is the standard for this project. It shares the same Vite config and plugin chain as the application, giving it accurate module resolution and TypeScript support.

### Vitest configuration in `vite.config.ts`

```ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vite-plus'

export default defineConfig({
  test: {
    include: ['src/**/*.test.ts', 'tests/**/*.test.ts'],
    coverage: {
      provider: 'v8',
      reporter: ['text', 'html'],
      include: ['src/**/*.ts'],
      exclude: ['src/**/*.test.ts', 'src/db/migrations/**', 'src/db/seed/**'],
    },
  },
})
```

